Connecting Virtual Networks

Now in your professional workloads, you will encounter multiple accounts and subscriptions. Why is this relevant? because on one company lets say chances are that's their exact network structure for the company. It's not a one stop shop for all of the company's needs. So you will most definitely encounter multiple virtual networks in different subscriptions. Now traditionally you could do two things network wise for very high level stuff it's either do site to site vpns or expressroute all the way. Both are absolutely terrible for what you want to do for completely different reasons. site to site throttles your bandwidth because the traffic has to go through a tunnel and therefore consume additional computing power. EXPRESSROUTE is well, if your vnets are just in the same region or even in the same data center and you want them to be able to talk to each other and you route them like that? you're basically taking the long long way to transmit the same data which means ungodly amounts of latency. Think about it this way, if you wanted to send a cake to your friend for his birthday would you rather either send it through fedex which is stupid and takes ages when he's just your neighbor or would you wait for other neighbors to visit his house to wait and ask them to help you send a cake bit by bit? hell no! there's a better way to give him the cake and that's by visiting his house directly and that's what we're going to transition to Peering

Peering

Virtual Network Peering is establishing a relationship between two virtual networks, but of course as a cynic would say almost all are transactional but in this case it is true since you're paying for data you ingress or egress per gb. When you're establishing these peering relationships between vnets, absolutely don't let the address species for these overlap like at all. Otherwise, the peering won't work. There is a way for certain ranges to overlap and that's where the grandkids method comes into play. so if you have a parent vnet and two kid vnets those kid vnets can peer to the same grandkid vnet. Further more, if you have vnet 1,2 and 3 you peer them as vnet 1, then vnet 2 and then to vnet 3 in a sequence. Vnet 1 cannot talk to vnet 3 since the peering relationship is not transitive.

There's also subnet-level peering which is a very handy thing, you just need on the interface to set a setting called peer complete vnet to false and then you choose which subnets through their names you want to connect. Because god forbid there are some vnets whose ip address spaces do overlap, however you can just peer their respective subnets that dont overlap instead.

